the AIN and the Aleph.

00:22:38.693 --> 00:22:40.154
And it's a little more complicated than

00:22:40.174 --> 00:22:41.256
that because, uh,

00:22:42.017 --> 00:22:42.758
Over the years,

00:22:43.018 --> 00:22:47.785
Hebrew originally had a shin and a shemek.

00:22:48.005 --> 00:22:49.807
The shin was the S-H and the shemek

00:22:49.827 --> 00:22:50.548
was the H sound,

00:22:50.848 --> 00:22:52.191
but they added a sin.

00:22:52.811 --> 00:22:54.453
And that's really a challenge now in

00:22:54.473 --> 00:22:56.416
translation because you take a word like

00:22:56.557 --> 00:22:56.957
Nassau.

00:22:58.196 --> 00:23:00.019
It's typically in the verbal form,

00:23:00.118 --> 00:23:04.801
it's rendered by the Masoretes as N-A-S-A.

00:23:05.722 --> 00:23:08.384
But in the original Paleo-Hebrew,

00:23:09.645 --> 00:23:13.367
the S-H and the S would have been

00:23:13.468 --> 00:23:14.348
identical, same letter.

00:23:15.390 --> 00:23:16.530
And if you wanted the S sound

00:23:16.631 --> 00:23:19.212
independently, you would go to the Samak.

00:23:19.752 --> 00:23:22.334
uh and one of those words because you

00:23:22.354 --> 00:23:23.713
know this is it's one of the two

00:23:23.753 --> 00:23:25.134
words that are found in the third

